1
00:00:00,799 --> 00:00:06,340
Heikin-ashi is a visual representation which
clearly shows trends and reversals.

2
00:00:06,340 --> 00:00:11,290
More importantly, it is a quantifiable technique
that is easy to implement and use.

3
00:00:11,290 --> 00:00:17,150
While traditional price candles appeal to
the more artistic and subjective judgement,

4
00:00:17,150 --> 00:00:21,529
Heikin-Ashi is a far more evident way to display
trends and reversals.

5
00:00:21,529 --> 00:00:27,640
Japanese candlestick patterns have very flexible
rules and interpretations "in the context."

6
00:00:27,640 --> 00:00:31,640
everyone translates them, more or less, in
a subjective manner.

7
00:00:31,640 --> 00:00:35,530
My personal interpretations may be different
from yours.

8
00:00:35,530 --> 00:00:41,129
These facts lead to the reality that candlestick
patterns are subjective, artistic, and challenging,

9
00:00:41,129 --> 00:00:45,390
so traders need a more objective, quantifiable
tool.

10
00:00:45,390 --> 00:00:47,609
And that tool is the Heikin Ashi.

11
00:00:47,609 --> 00:00:52,379
The very simple quantification makes the Heikin
Ashi technique attractive to those who tend

12
00:00:52,379 --> 00:00:56,489
to take a more analytical, more precise approach.

13
00:00:56,489 --> 00:01:03,530
Any heikin-ashi chart filters out price noise;
as a result, trends, consolidations, and reversals

14
00:01:03,530 --> 00:01:06,490
are more visible and clearer to the naked
eye.

15
00:01:06,490 --> 00:01:11,530
Sentiment, trend, and momentum are three elements
every trader should take into account-and

16
00:01:11,530 --> 00:01:15,320
all are addressed by heikin-ashi.

17
00:01:15,320 --> 00:01:21,760
A big advantage of the Japanese candles is
that they show participants' sentiment.

18
00:01:21,760 --> 00:01:27,260
Candle color and body length are reliable
measures for determining the degree of bullishness

19
00:01:27,260 --> 00:01:29,060
or bearishness.

20
00:01:29,060 --> 00:01:35,440
Long-body candles with no or small shadows
appear as a result of strong buying or selling.

21
00:01:35,440 --> 00:01:41,250
Excessive shadows or wicks underscore buyers'
and sellers' mood swings.

22
00:01:41,250 --> 00:01:45,690
A doji shows indecision or waiting for the
next action.

23
00:01:45,690 --> 00:01:51,030
The closing price relative to the open is
a clear indication about the bullish or bearish

24
00:01:51,030 --> 00:01:54,750
clouds hanging above the trading period.

25
00:01:54,750 --> 00:01:59,690
Heikin-ashi candles make it easier to identify
and follow trends.

26
00:01:59,690 --> 00:02:03,640
Green bodies with no lower shadows show an
uptrend.

27
00:02:03,640 --> 00:02:09,920
On the other hand, red bodies with no upper
shadows represent the price being in a short

28
00:02:09,920 --> 00:02:11,270
or longer downtrend.

29
00:02:11,270 --> 00:02:19,210
A doji-like modified candle with shadows emerging
after an uptrend or downtrend suggests a reversal.

30
00:02:19,210 --> 00:02:25,700
Finally, price consolidations are translated
as sequences of two or more heikin-ashi doji-like

31
00:02:25,700 --> 00:02:26,810
candles.

32
00:02:26,810 --> 00:02:31,750
With heikin-ashi candles, the sentiment is
measured by the color and size of the candle

33
00:02:31,750 --> 00:02:35,560
bodies together with the position of the shadows.

34
00:02:35,560 --> 00:02:41,640
Big green and red bodies are features of solid
underlying trends.

35
00:02:41,640 --> 00:02:44,650
Smaller bodies warn about trend exhaustion.

36
00:02:44,650 --> 00:02:51,410
A doji-like candle that follows a sequence
of green or red modified candles raises caution

37
00:02:51,410 --> 00:02:57,480
about either a reversal or the beginning of
a consolidation.

38
00:02:57,480 --> 00:03:02,840
While Japanese candlestick theory requires
many definitions and flexible interpretation

39
00:03:02,840 --> 00:03:08,790
rules for most common and exotic patterns,
the heikin-ashi technique works with only

40
00:03:08,790 --> 00:03:10,290
the five simple rules.

41
00:03:10,290 --> 00:03:11,290
1.

42
00:03:11,290 --> 00:03:14,850
A sequence of green bodies identifies an uptrend.

43
00:03:14,850 --> 00:03:18,550
A sequence of red bodies identifies a downtrend.

44
00:03:18,550 --> 00:03:19,550
2.

45
00:03:19,550 --> 00:03:25,319
The uptrend gets stronger with longer green
bodies and no lower shadows.

46
00:03:25,319 --> 00:03:30,100
The downtrend gets stronger with longer red
bodies and no upper shadows.

47
00:03:30,100 --> 00:03:31,100
3.

48
00:03:31,100 --> 00:03:36,590
The trend gets weaker with smaller bodies
and, possibly, with the emergence of both

49
00:03:36,590 --> 00:03:38,170
lower and upper shadows.

50
00:03:38,170 --> 00:03:39,170
4.

51
00:03:39,170 --> 00:03:44,850
A consolidation is revealed when a series
of smaller bodies with both upper and lower

52
00:03:44,850 --> 00:03:46,140
shadows emerge.

53
00:03:46,140 --> 00:03:47,140
5.

54
00:03:47,140 --> 00:03:52,770
A trend reversal is likely with the emergence
of a small body with long upper and lower

55
00:03:52,770 --> 00:03:59,069
shadows (doji-like candle) or a sudden color
change.

56
00:03:59,069 --> 00:04:04,640
Multiple time frame analysis in trading requires
an increased attention because of the better

57
00:04:04,640 --> 00:04:08,450
odds in catching trends and remaining in them
longer.

58
00:04:08,450 --> 00:04:12,850
Obviously if an uptrend is just starting in
daily (tfi), weekly (tf2), and monthly (tf3)

59
00:04:12,850 --> 00:04:18,209
time frames, the winning odds for a long entry
now are far bigger than when the entry is

60
00:04:18,209 --> 00:04:24,240
initiated in a daily time frame with weekly
and monthly charts casting bearish signals.

61
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:30,599
The ideal scenario is to have trend alignment
in all three time horizons and to initiate

62
00:04:30,599 --> 00:04:33,580
the trade as early as possible in the trend.

63
00:04:33,580 --> 00:04:39,250
As a compromise, two consecutive time frames
may replace the ideal scenario.

64
00:04:39,250 --> 00:04:45,979
So, one option is to work only with two consecutive
time frames instead of three and to apply

65
00:04:45,979 --> 00:04:50,520
a simple strategy:
• buy when the current modified candle color

66
00:04:50,520 --> 00:04:55,449
changes from red to green in the two consecutive
time frames.

67
00:04:55,449 --> 00:05:00,439
• sell when the current modified candle
color changes from green to red in the two

68
00:05:00,439 --> 00:05:04,289
consecutive time frames.

69
00:05:04,289 --> 00:05:08,319
Another great strategy involves the RSI indicator.

70
00:05:08,319 --> 00:05:14,620
There are three horizontal lines plotted on
RSI indicator window: 30, 50, and 70.

71
00:05:14,620 --> 00:05:21,249
RSI 50 level can be used as a strong tool
to confirm the different kinds of trade setups

72
00:05:21,249 --> 00:05:22,889
using Heikin Ashi.

73
00:05:22,889 --> 00:05:28,349
I mainly prefer to use the relative strength
index (RSI) indicator for centerline crossovers.

74
00:05:28,349 --> 00:05:33,690
A movement from below the centerline (50)
to above indicates a rising trend.

75
00:05:33,690 --> 00:05:39,360
A rising centerline crossover occurs when
the RSI value crosses above the 50 line on

76
00:05:39,360 --> 00:05:42,389
the scale, moving towards the 70 line.

77
00:05:42,389 --> 00:05:48,089
This indicates the market trend is increasing
in strength, and is seen as a bullish signal

78
00:05:48,089 --> 00:05:51,710
until the RSI approaches the 70 line.

79
00:05:51,710 --> 00:05:56,699
A movement from above the centerline (50)
to below indicates a falling trend.

80
00:05:56,699 --> 00:06:02,589
A falling centerline crossover occurs when
the RSI value crosses below the 50 line on

81
00:06:02,589 --> 00:06:06,289
the scale, moving towards the 30 line.

82
00:06:06,289 --> 00:06:11,930
This indicates the market trend is weakening
in strength, and is seen as a bearish signal

83
00:06:11,930 --> 00:06:16,729
until the RSI approaches the 30 line.

84
00:06:16,729 --> 00:06:21,869
A simple strategy would be to
• buy when the current modified candle color

85
00:06:21,869 --> 00:06:28,039
changes from red to green and the RSI is above
50

86
00:06:28,039 --> 00:06:33,389
• sell when the current modified candle
color changes from green to red and the RSI

87
00:06:33,389 --> 00:06:35,860
in below 50.

88
00:06:35,860 --> 00:06:40,550
This way you have additional confirmation
that you are in a healthy trend, determined

89
00:06:40,550 --> 00:06:44,449
by both Heikin Ashi and RSI centerline.

90
00:06:44,449 --> 00:06:49,819
For an uptrend, you want to see the Heikin
Ashi trend built primarily by bullish candles

91
00:06:49,819 --> 00:06:55,400
and absent of lower candlewicks, with the
RSI above 50.

92
00:06:55,400 --> 00:07:01,080
When the price is shooting up, the price action
creates very little to no lower shadows.

93
00:07:01,080 --> 00:07:07,800
The bearish scenario has the same functions
as the bullish one but in the opposite direction.

94
00:07:07,800 --> 00:07:12,669
This means that it is built mainly by bearish
Heikin Ashi candles.

95
00:07:12,669 --> 00:07:17,849
You want to see a strong bearish trend on
the Heikin Ashi graph that has very little

96
00:07:17,849 --> 00:07:23,870
to no upper candle shadows, in addition to
the RSI below 50 level.

97
00:07:23,870 --> 00:07:25,300
Simple, and powerful.

98
00:07:25,300 --> 00:07:46,809
Here are some examples of uptrends and downtrends,
using this approach.

99
00:07:46,809 --> 00:07:50,749
The second strategy involves the Ichimoku
indicator.

100
00:07:50,749 --> 00:07:55,710
The Ichimoku cloud consists of several components
which give it a unique capacity to detect

101
00:07:55,710 --> 00:07:58,629
trends, to determine whether we are in a trend,
its direction and when the trend reverses.

102
00:07:58,629 --> 00:08:05,800
One of the components is the Kumo cloud which
is one of the most unique aspects of the Ichimoku.

103
00:08:05,800 --> 00:08:12,339
The Kumo is typically looked at in terms of
support and resistance; if it is thick, then

104
00:08:12,339 --> 00:08:17,559
the support/resistance is strong (depending
on the position of price in relation to the

105
00:08:17,559 --> 00:08:18,559
cloud).

106
00:08:18,559 --> 00:08:24,319
By contrast, if it is thin, then the s/r levels
are considered weak.

107
00:08:24,319 --> 00:08:30,449
Generally, if the price is above the Kumo,
then there is an uptrend in place and/or more

108
00:08:30,449 --> 00:08:31,849
buying opportunities.

109
00:08:31,849 --> 00:08:38,260
If the price is below the Kumo, then it is
under resistance and it is better to be looking

110
00:08:38,260 --> 00:08:41,810
for shorts instead of longs.

111
00:08:41,810 --> 00:08:47,310
The longer price action stays above or below
the Kumo, the stronger the trend and the more

112
00:08:47,310 --> 00:08:52,050
support/resistance the Kumo offers.

113
00:08:52,050 --> 00:08:57,180
A simple strategy would be to
• buy when the current modified candle color

114
00:08:57,180 --> 00:09:03,379
changes from red to green, Kumo cloud is green
and price is above the cloud

115
00:09:03,379 --> 00:09:10,430
• sell when the current modified candle
color changes from green to red, Kumo cloud

116
00:09:10,430 --> 00:09:16,339
is red and price is below the cloud
For an uptrend, you want to see the Heikin

117
00:09:16,339 --> 00:09:23,060
Ashi trend built primarily by bullish candles
and absent of lower candlewicks, and the candles

118
00:09:23,060 --> 00:09:25,209
above the Kumo cloud.

119
00:09:25,209 --> 00:09:31,370
A strong bearish trend consists of Heikin
Ashi that has very little to no upper candle

120
00:09:31,370 --> 00:09:34,670
shadows, in addition to the price below Kumo
cloud.

121
00:09:34,670 --> 00:09:36,470
Again, simple, and effective.

122
00:09:36,470 --> 00:09:58,029
